%N A284287 Number of possible legal open chains of a set of dominoes tiles with 0 to 2n pips.
%C A284287 a(3) corresponds to the standard double-six set of 28 tiles. The question for its value was asked by Louis Poinsot in 1809 and by Orly Terquem in 1849 and was first calculated by Michel Reiss in 1859 (published in 1871).
%C A284287 The problem of finding a(2) appears in Henry Dudeney's book.
%C A284287 a(4) was calculated by Gaston Tarry in 1886.
%C A284287 The number of legally closed chains is a(n)/((n+1)*(2n+1)) = n^(2n+1) * A135388(n) (i.e., divided by the number of tiles in the set, A000217(2n+1)) = 2, 8448, 284258211840, 238949513827774680268800, ... .
%C A284287 If reverse order is not counted, the number of open chains is a(n)/2 = 6, 63360, 3979614965760, 5376364061124930306048000, ..., and the number of closed chains is a(n)/(2*(n+1)*(2n+1)) = 1, 4224, 142129105920, 119474756913887340134400, ... .
